To find the inverse of a 2x2 matrix A = \begin{bmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \\ \end{bmatrix}, we can use the formula:

A⁻¹ = \frac{1}{ad - bc} \begin{bmatrix} d & -b \\ -c & a \\ \end{bmatrix}

In this case, A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 & 5 \\ 1 & 3 \\ \end{bmatrix}, so a = 2, b = 5, c = 1, and d = 3.

First, we need to find the determinant (ad - bc):

Determinant = (2 * 3) - (5 * 1) = 6 - 5 = 1

Since the determinant is non-zero, the inverse exists. Now, we can find the inverse using the formula:

A⁻¹ = \frac{1}{1} \begin{bmatrix} 3 & -5 \\ -1 & 2 \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 & -5 \\ -1 & 2 \\ \end{bmatrix}

So, the inverse of A is:

A⁻¹ = \begin{bmatrix} 3 & -5 \\ -1 & 2 \\ \end{bmatrix}
